{
  "text": "Security groups are stateful firewalls that act at the instance level. Think of them as virtual firewalls for your EC2 instances. They're stateful, meaning if you allow traffic out, the response is automatically allowed back in. Security groups are evaluated first before network ACLs, and they support both allow rules only, you can't explicitly deny traffic. Each instance can have multiple security groups, and rules are evaluated together. This is your primary security mechanism for controlling access to your instances.",
